People participate in a protest against the collapse of the national currency in front of the Central Bank "Banque du Liban" in Beirut, Lebanon, Jan. 8, 2022.(Photo: Xinhua)France and Saudi Arabia agreed to provide emergency financial support for humanitarian projects in Lebanon amid a severe economic crisis, the French embassy in Lebanon said Tuesday.The projects will be dedicated to supporting multiple primary health centers in Lebanon and providing emergency financial and food aid for the most vulnerable Lebanese people, the embassy said in a statement.The agreement was reached on Monday during talks held between French Foreign Minister Jean-Yves le Drian and his Saudi counterpart Prince Faisal bin Farhan Al Saud in Paris, it noted."These joint humanitarian projects represent the first step towards a greater joint mobilization on the part of France and Saudi Arabia amid Lebanon's severe crisis. In this spirit, a joint support mechanism will be established for associations working in the field to meet the needs of the Lebanese population," said the embassy.Lebanon has been going through an unprecedented financial crisis that has plunged over 74 percent of the Lebanese population into poverty, according to the United Nations.Lebanon is negotiating with the International Monetary Fund in the hope to unlock billions of US dollars in aid to save the country from collapse.Xinhua